<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="331" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,151,645]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,222,248]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Description.</emphasis>
Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[509,593,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURES 35–37" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1335,1359]" captionTargetBox="[158,1428,536,1307]" captionTargetId="figure-178@20.[150,1437,525,1312]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 35–37. Trichotichnus spp., habitus. 35, T. cyrtops (Tschitschérine, 1906) (Yunnan); 36, T. doiinthanonensis Ito, 1997 (Dulongjiang); 37, T. fedorenkoi sp. n. (Tam Dao). Scale bar = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6781715" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6781715/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
. Morphological character states are as described for 
<taxonomicName authority="Kataev &amp; Hongbin &amp; Wrase, 2022" authorityName="Kataev &amp; Hongbin &amp; Wrase" authorityYear="2022" box="[1190,1313,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Trichotichnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="331" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schmidti" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1190,1313,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">T. schmidti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1321,1386,223,249]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1321,1386,223,249]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, but differing as follows.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,151,645]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">
Body larger (length 
<quantity box="[426,565,294,321]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.8" metricValueMax="9.1" metricValueMin="8.5" pageId="30" pageNumber="331" unit="mm" value="8.8" valueMax="9.1" valueMin="8.5">8.5–9.1 mm</quantity>
). Dorsal microsculpture highly obliterated, meshes on head almost not recognized. Mesotarsomere 
<quantity box="[406,449,331,357]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="30" pageNumber="331" unit="in" value="3.0">3 in</quantity>
male more elongate, in most specimens longer than wide. Last abdominal sternite (VII) in both sexes rounded at apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,151,645]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">
Median lobe of aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[501,638,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 68–72" captionStartId="30.[151,264,1505,1529]" captionTargetBox="[161,1425,679,1472]" captionTargetId="figure-216@30.[151,1436,669,1482]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURES 68–72. Trichotichnus fedorenkoi sp. n. 68, terminal lamella of aedeagus; 69 &amp; 70, median lobe of aedeagus (holo- type); 71, gonocoxite; 72, laterotergite, gonosubcoxite, and gonocoxite (env. Cat Cat). Dorsal (68 &amp; 70), lateral (69 &amp; 71) and ventral (72) views. Scale bars: A = 0.5 mm (68, 71 &amp; 72), B = 1.0 mm (69 &amp; 70)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6781741" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6781741/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Figs. 68–70</figureCitation>
) in lateral view slightly arcuate, with almost straight apical half; apex thin, hooked ventrally; in dorsal view median lobe comparatively wide basally, evenly narrowed apically, with terminal lamella (
<figureCitation box="[322,404,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 68–72" captionStartId="30.[151,264,1505,1529]" captionTargetBox="[161,1425,679,1472]" captionTargetId="figure-216@30.[151,1436,669,1482]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURES 68–72. Trichotichnus fedorenkoi sp. n. 68, terminal lamella of aedeagus; 69 &amp; 70, median lobe of aedeagus (holo- type); 71, gonocoxite; 72, laterotergite, gonosubcoxite, and gonocoxite (env. Cat Cat). Dorsal (68 &amp; 70), lateral (69 &amp; 71) and ventral (72) views. Scale bars: A = 0.5 mm (68, 71 &amp; 72), B = 1.0 mm (69 &amp; 70)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6781741" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6781741/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Fig. 68</figureCitation>
) about as wide as long, roundly narrowed at apex. Ventral side edged laterally and slightly depressed between margins. Apical orifice in dorsal position, wide apically. Internal sac with a large curved spiny patch apically, narrowed to base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,151,645]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">
. Female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[401,561,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURES 68–72" captionStartId="30.[151,264,1505,1529]" captionTargetBox="[161,1425,679,1472]" captionTargetId="figure-216@30.[151,1436,669,1482]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURES 68–72. Trichotichnus fedorenkoi sp. n. 68, terminal lamella of aedeagus; 69 &amp; 70, median lobe of aedeagus (holo- type); 71, gonocoxite; 72, laterotergite, gonosubcoxite, and gonocoxite (env. Cat Cat). Dorsal (68 &amp; 70), lateral (69 &amp; 71) and ventral (72) views. Scale bars: A = 0.5 mm (68, 71 &amp; 72), B = 1.0 mm (69 &amp; 70)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6781741" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6781741/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Figs. 71 &amp; 72</figureCitation>
): gonocoxite comparatively narrow in ventral view, about 0.6 times as long as gonosubcoxite, with relatively narrower base.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6781741" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6781741" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6781741/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="331" startId="30.[151,264,1505,1529]" targetBox="[161,1425,679,1472]" targetPageId="30">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,1505,1602]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,341,1505,1530]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">FIGURES 68–72.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Kataev &amp; Hongbin &amp; Wrase, 2022" authorityName="Kataev &amp; Hongbin &amp; Wrase" authorityYear="2022" box="[347,600,1506,1530]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Trichotichnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="331" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fedorenkoi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[347,600,1506,1530]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Trichotichnus fedorenkoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[608,665,1506,1530]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[608,665,1506,1530]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
68, terminal lamella of aedeagus; 69 &amp; 70, median lobe of aedeagus (holotype); 71, gonocoxite; 72, laterotergite, gonosubcoxite, and gonocoxite (env. Cat Cat). Dorsal (68 &amp; 70), lateral (69 &amp; 71) and ventral (72) views. Scale bars: A = 0.5 mm (68, 71 &amp; 72), B = 1.0 mm (69 &amp; 70).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,1648,1890]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">
Proportions (
<specimenCount box="[345,432,1648,1674]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331" type="male">2 males</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[487,595,1648,1674]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331" type="female">3 females</specimenCount>
measured): HWmax/PWmax 0.69–0.73; HWmin/PWmax 0.52–0.57; HWmax/HWmin 1.27–1.32; PWmax/PL 1.53–1.57; PWmax/PWmin 1.21–1.28; EL/EW 1.52–1.60; EL/PL 2.92–3.19; EW/PWmax 1.27–1.33.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="331" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,1648,1890]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1756,1782]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named after our friend and colleague Dmitry Fedorenko (
<collectingRegion box="[1176,1278,1756,1782]" country="Russia" name="Moscow" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Moscow</collectingRegion>
), an excellent carabidologist, who collected a part of the 
<typeStatus box="[629,677,1792,1818]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">type</typeStatus>
series.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="331" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,1648,1890]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1828,1854]" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Distribution</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[360,445,1828,1854]" captionStart="FIGURE 73" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1841,1865]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-19@31.[151,1435,181,1817]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 73. Trichotichnus spp., distribution: T. doiinthanonensis Ito, 1997 (circles); T. fedorenkoi sp. n. (squares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6781743" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6781743/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Fig. 73</figureCitation>
). Known from North 
<collectingCountry box="[685,780,1828,1854]" name="Vietnam" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[795,888,1828,1854]" country="Vietnam" name="Lao Cai" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Lao Cai</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[899,1013,1828,1854]" country="Vietnam" name="Cao Bang" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Cao Bang</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1023,1140,1828,1854]" country="Vietnam" name="Vinh Phuc" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Vinh Phuc</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1194,1311,1828,1854]" country="Vietnam" name="Ninh Binh" pageId="30" pageNumber="331">Ninh Binh</collectingRegion>
provinces) where it occurs at altitudes of about 
<quantity box="[558,702,1864,1890]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.45" metricValueMax="17.0" metricValueMin="1.9" pageId="30" pageNumber="331" unit="m" value="945.0" valueMax="1700.0" valueMin="190.0">190–1700 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
